<br>
In my evaluations, the &quot;optimum&quot; system would be a Pentium IV processor at 1.2 ghz or better, 768 MB RAM @ 133mhz+(yes 768!) , 64 MB video card (AGP or PCI), and a 7200RPM Hard drive.  That is the lowest end system I have seen that allows you to keep all the extras turned on and have a jitter free gaming experience with EQ.  Many of you are saying &quot;This is bull shit, I cant afford all this!&quot;  I agree, this game has become a hog to play with all the enhancements turned on.  Some of you will remember when 16 megs of RAM was quite a bit.  Things change.  VI just did a bad job at preparing the customers well enough ahead of time.<br>
<br>
If you turn off all the enhancements, MIP Mapping, Level of Detail, 3D sky, various chat filters like Damage Shields and your misses etc, none of the new character models, lower your clip plane to 75% or lower, and reduce the sound quality to 50%, you can run this game quite well on any modern PC with 256 megs of RAM.<br>
<br>
If you are having a lot of problems, turn everything off.  Lower everything to the lowest possible state.  Then, simply turn things on one-by-one based on your priorities.  As soon as you get to the point where you cant add any more items because of quality, take the last few off and there you have it.  Do this in a zone like Burning Woods where the video lag is bad anyways.  That will give you somewhat of a worse case scenario.<br>
<br>
If you are using Windows 9x or Windows ME, make sure all of the &quot;background&quot; programs are off.  You can do this by hitting &quot;CTRL&quot; + &quot;ALT&quot; + &quot;DEL&quot; at the same time.  You will see the ability to highlight programs that are secretly running in the background and end them one-by-one.  The only 2 you MUST leave alone in that list is &quot;systray&quot; and &quot;explorer&quot;.  End Task all the other programs running.  You may need to end task specific programs more than once to get it to actually close.  This is a pain in the arse, but it stops other programs from eating up your extra memory. <br>
<br>
If you have a PC based firewall on the computer you are using to play EQ, you will need to disable it while playing EQ if you want to free up more resources.<br>
<br>
I hope this helps some people.  I personally use a dual Xeon processor system to play the game, but that is obviously not the norm.  If you have any questions, please feel free to let me know.  I will do my best to answer them for you.  You can email me at oriathin@cs.com.  I am not EQ support, but I definitely have a lot of computer knowledge and experience.<br>
